\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Measuring Geometric Phase using 3 Pin Holes :.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We describe a method a of measuring the geometric phase optically, using
 3 pin holes.
 This method is in stark contrast with conventional methods where states
 are evolved and the relative phase measured after completion of a cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Geometric Phase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concept of geometric phase was discovered as a relative phase that is introduced
 in an adiabatic and cyclic evolution of a state, between the final and
 initial state.
 This relative phase has both the geometric phase and what is known as the
 dynamic phase, which is the time integral of the Hamiltonian.
 The concept since then, has been generalized to work in cases of non-adiabatic
 evolution and then even to non-cyclic evolution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conventional Measurement Scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimentally, conventional measurement of the geometric phase is associated
 with directly measuring the total phase difference between the evolved
 and unevolved reference states.
 This requires phase calibration, which is an experimental complication.
 Further, one must eliminate the dynamic phase to obtain the geometric phase.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Kinematic Geometric Phase and the Proposed Scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Direct observation of geometric phases using a three-pinhole interferometer
 
\series bold
PHYSICAL REVIEW A 81, 012104 (2010)
\series default
, 
\emph on
Kobayashi et.
 al.

\emph default
 propose a method of measurement of geometric phase, which is built on the
 kinematic approach to geometric phase.
 In this approach, the geometric phase is attributed to the structure of
 the Hilbert space itself and doesn't require dynamics (evolution of states).
 One can show that Geometric Phase is a ray space object and more explicitly,
 it has been shown that for n points in the ray space, there exists an entity
 known as the Bargmann invariant, from which the geometric phase can be
 recovered.
 This geometric phase is that for a closed curve obtained by connecting
 the n points with geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed scheme involves use of 3 quantum states and letting them interfere
 directly, viz.
 without evolving the system.
 From the intereferogram thus obtained, using the 3 vertex Bargmann invariant
 and some more details specific to the setup, it has been shown that the
 geometric phase can be recovered.
 Further, since the initial 3 states are known, one can theoretically evaluate
 the Geometric phase.
 Theory and experimental observations have been shown to agree.
 Since this method doesn't require evolution, the need for phase calibration
 and removal of dynamic phase has been eliminated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Geometric Phase and Bargmann Invariant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename paperImages/1.png
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic of the setup
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As Figure 1 shows, three states 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}}(j=1,2,3)$
\end_inset

 represent the internal states of the photon from three pinholes.
 The resultant interferogram should and does contain three distinct interference
 fringes due to each pinhole pair.
 To start with, superimpostion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and a 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)=e^{i\phi}$
\end_inset

 shifted 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 leads to an intensity of 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\propto1+\left|\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right|\cos\left(\phi+\arg\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right)
\]

\end_inset

which can be derived easily as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\left|\psi\right\rangle  & =e^{i\phi}\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle +\left|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \\
\left\langle \psi|\psi\right\rangle  & =\left(\left\langle \psi_{1}\right|e^{-i\phi}+\left\langle \psi_{2}\right|\right)\left(e^{i\phi}\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle +\left|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right)\\
 & =\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{1}\right\rangle +\left\langle \psi_{2}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle +\left(e^{-i\phi}e^{i\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle }\left|\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right|+\text{hc}\right)\\
 & \propto1+\left|\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right|\cos\left(\phi+\arg\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Thus the interference fringes are shifted by the relative phase between
 the states.
 In case of constructive interference, this phase is zero and the states
 are called 
\emph on
in phase
\emph default
.
 Note however that this property of the states is 
\emph on
non transitive
\emph default
.
 To make this explicit, consider the following expression, which is manifestly
 invariant under a local change of phases (gauge invariance).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\Delta_{3}\left(\psi_{1},\psi_{2},\psi_{3}\right) & \equiv\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{2}|\psi_{3}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{3}|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \\
 & =\text{tr}\left(\left|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{2}|\psi_{3}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{3}|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{1}\right|\right)\\
\implies\text{arg}\left(\Delta_{3}\left(\psi_{1},\psi_{2},\psi_{3}\right)\right) & =\arg\left(\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{2}|\psi_{3}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{3}|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \right)\\
 & =\sum_{(i,j)\text{cycle}}\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{j}|\psi_{j}\right\rangle 
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Here, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{2}|\psi_{3}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

, that is if the states 1 and 2 are in phase, 2 and 3 are in phase, then
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{arg}\left(\Delta_{3}\left(\psi_{1},\psi_{2},\psi_{3}\right)\right)=\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{3}\right\rangle \ne0$
\end_inset

 in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{3}$
\end_inset

 is defined to be a 3 point 
\series bold
Bargmann Invariant
\series default
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\arg\Delta_{3}$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
Pancharatnam Phase
\series default
.
 We recall/claim that the Pancharatnam phase can be related to the geometric
 phase corresponding to that of a triangle in the B space (or if you like,
 that of a system whose trajectory is given by the triangle).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
B `space' is a 
\emph on
subset
\emph default
 of H (Hilbert Space) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \psi|\psi\right\rangle =1$
\end_inset

.
 Ray space is the subspace formed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\psi}=\ket{\psi}\bra{\psi}$
\end_inset

 (idea is to remove the phase freedom)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This triangle has as vertices, the points corresponding to the 3 states.
 Its sides are formed by joining these points by geodesics.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Assuming an appropriately defined metric, this we had proved in the course.
 It hinges on the fact that for a closed loop in B space, the total phase
 is zero.
 In general 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{total}}=\phi_{\text{dyn}}+\phi_{\text{geom}}$
\end_inset

 where for a geodesic between 2 points, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{dyn}}=\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 With these assumptions and the fact that dynamic phase is additive, the
 result stated should follow.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The relation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{\text{goem}}=-\text{arg}\Delta_{3}\left(\psi_{1},\psi_{2},\psi_{3}\right)
\]

\end_inset

It can be further shown, that for a two state system (such as polarization
 of photon, the case here), 
\begin_inset Formula $\arg\Delta_{3}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the solid angle (
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

) of the spherical triangle on the Bloch sphere with the three states as
 the vertices.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{\text{goem}}=-\frac{\Omega}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Geometric Phase and Ridge Lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider again, the three pinholes irradiated with monochromatic light of
 wavenumber 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Without any loss of generality, the location of the three pinholes can
 be parametrized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}(j=1,2,3)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{a}_{j}\right|=a\,\forall\,j$
\end_inset

, by simply choosing the origin to be the circumcenter of the triangle.
 The source plane is labeled to be at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 It is known that the state of a photon can be expressed as a combination
 of a spatial part represented by the spherical wave and the internal, polarizat
ion state part.
 The state of photon from the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 pin-hole
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If we assume that all the pinholes have the same probability of transmission
\end_layout

\end_inset

, on the observation plane 
\begin_inset Formula $z=L$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\psi(\mathbf{r})\right\rangle =C\sum_{j=1}^{3}\frac{\text{exp}\left[i\left(k\left|\mathbf{R}-\mathbf{a}_{j}\right|+\phi_{j}\right)\right]}{\left|\mathbf{R}-\mathbf{a}_{j}\right|}\left|\psi_{j}\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 is the position vector on the observation plane (
\begin_inset Formula $z=L$
\end_inset

); 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}\equiv\mathbf{R}-\left(\mathbf{R}.\mathbf{z}\right)\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

 (component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 perpendicular to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

, the unit vector along z-axis); 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is dimensionless normalization; 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the phase of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{j}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (the polarization state of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 source).
 If we make the para-axial approximation, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\mathbf{R}-\mathbf{a}_{j} & =\left(L\mathbf{z}+\mathbf{r}\right)-\mathbf{a}_{j}\\
\left|\mathbf{R}-\mathbf{a}_{j}\right| & =\left[\left(\left(L\mathbf{z}+\mathbf{r}\right)-\mathbf{a}_{j}\right)\left(\left(L\mathbf{z}+\mathbf{r}\right)-\mathbf{a}_{j}\right)\right]^{1/2}\\
 & =\left[\left(L\mathbf{z}+\mathbf{r}\right)\left(L\mathbf{z}+\mathbf{r}\right)-2\left(L\mathbf{z}+\mathbf{r}\right)\mathbf{a}_{j}+\mathbf{a}_{j}^{2}\right]^{1/2}\\
 & =\left[L^{2}+2L\cancelto{0}{\mathbf{z}.\mathbf{r}}+\mathbf{r}^{2}-2(L\cancelto{0}{\mathbf{z}.\mathbf{r}}+\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})+\mathbf{a}_{j}^{2}\right]^{1/2}\\
 & =\left[L^{2}+2\frac{r^{2}+a^{2}}{2}-2(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})\right]^{1/2}\\
 & =L\left[1+2\left(\frac{r^{2}+a^{2}}{2L^{2}}-\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})}{L^{2}}\right)\right]^{1/2}\\
 & \approx L\left[1+\frac{r^{2}+a^{2}}{2L^{2}}-\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})}{L^{2}}\right]\\
 & =L+\frac{r^{2}+a^{2}}{2L}-\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})}{L}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\psi(\mathbf{r})\right\rangle \approx C\sum_{j=1}^{3}\frac{\text{exp}\left[i\left(k\left(L+\frac{r^{2}+a^{2}}{2L}-\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})}{L}\right)+\phi_{j}\right)\right]}{L}\left|\psi_{j}\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

where we've used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}^{2}=a^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In the last step, in writing the denominator approximately as 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, we have also used a stronger condition, that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{R}-\mathbf{a}_{j}\right|\ll\left(L^{3}/k\right)^{1/4}\ll L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intensity distribution can then be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}p(x,y) & =\left\langle \psi(\mathbf{r})|\psi(\mathbf{r})\right\rangle \\
 & =\frac{C^{2}}{L^{2}}\sum_{j,k=1}^{3}\text{exp}\left[-i\left(k\left(\cancel{L+\frac{r^{2}+a^{2}}{2L}}-\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})}{L}\right)+\phi_{j}\right)\right]\text{exp}\left[i\left(k\left(\cancel{L+\frac{r^{2}+a^{2}}{2L}}-\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{k})}{L}\right)+\phi_{k}\right)\right]\left\langle \psi_{j}|\psi_{k}\right\rangle \\
 & =\frac{C^{2}}{L^{2}}\left\{ 3+\sum_{j\neq k=1}^{3}\text{exp}\left[i\left(k\left(\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})}{L}-\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{k})}{L}\right)+\phi_{k}-\phi_{j}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{j}|\psi_{k}\right\rangle \right)\right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{j}|\psi_{k}\right\rangle \right|\right\} \\
 & =\frac{C^{2}}{L^{2}}\left\{ 3+\sum_{\left(j,k\right)\text{cycle}}\cos\left[k\left(\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{j})}{L}-\frac{(\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{a}_{k})}{L}\right)+\phi_{k}-\phi_{j}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{j}|\psi_{k}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{j}|\psi_{k}\right\rangle \right|\right\} \\
 & =\frac{C^{2}}{L^{2}}\left\{ -3+\sum_{(i,j)\text{cycle}}P_{ij}(x,y)\right\} 
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

which finally yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x,y)=\frac{C^{2}}{L^{2}}\left\{ -3+\sum_{(i,j)\text{cycle}}P_{ij}(x,y)\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{ij}(x,y)\equiv2\left(1+\cos\left[(\mathbf{k}_{ij}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{ij}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{i}|\psi_{j}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{i}|\psi_{j}\right\rangle \right|\right)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{ij}\equiv k(\mathbf{a}_{i}-\mathbf{a}_{j})/L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\equiv\phi_{i}-\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 This equation infact corresponds to that of the double slit interference
 fringes between two states 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the three pin hole interferogram consists of sets of interference
 fringes with distinct directions, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 Evidently, the geometric phase information is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 To extract this, we look at the condition for maximum intensity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\mathbf{k}_{ij}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{ij}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{i}|\psi_{j}\right\rangle =2n_{ij}\pi
\]

\end_inset

which is of the from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}.\mathbf{k}=c$
\end_inset

 (in 3d, this is a plane, in 2d, its a line obviously) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}(x\mathbf{x}+y\mathbf{y}).(k_{x}\mathbf{x}+k_{y}\mathbf{y}+k_{z}\mathbf{z}) & =c\\
 & =xk_{x}+yk_{y}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are integers.
 These equations define sets of three distinct parallel lines which are
 called the 
\series bold
ridge lines
\series default
 on the observation plane.
 The area 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of the triangle formed by these, called the 
\series bold
ridge triangle
\series default
.
 Using the formula for finding the area of a triangle, given equations of
 the lines making the edges as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}a_{1}x+b_{1}y+c_{1} & =0\\
a_{2}x+b_{2}y+c_{2} & =0\\
a_{3}x+b_{3}y+c_{3} & =0
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\text{det}\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{1} & b_{1} & c_{1}\\
a_{2} & b_{2} & c_{2}\\
a_{3} & b_{3} & c_{3}
\end{array}\right]^{2}}{2C_{1}C_{2}C_{3}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}=\text{cofactor of }c_{i}$
\end_inset

, we finally obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\frac{L^{2}}{4k^{2}S_{0}}\left\{ \text{arg}\left[\Delta_{3}\left(\psi_{1},\psi_{2},\psi_{3}\right)\right]-2n\pi\right\} ^{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=n_{12}+n_{23}+n_{31}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{o}$
\end_inset

 is the area of the triangle of the three pinholes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some points are wroth noting here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The area of ridge triangle is related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\arg\Delta_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 We define an 
\series bold
elemental ridge triangle
\series default
\emph on
 
\emph default
to be a ridge triangle that encloses no ridge lines.
 For example, for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\arg\Delta_{3}<2\pi$
\end_inset

 the ridge triangles with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 are elemental.
 Clearly, the 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 is proportional to square of geometric phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\arg\Delta_{3}$
\end_inset

; for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 it is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi-\arg\Delta_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Secondly, the gauge invariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{3}$
\end_inset

 carries over to the area since by introducing a phase shift to one of pinholes,
 two sets of ridge lines are displaced but the area is conserved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Third, the equation is proportional to the geometric phases regardless of
 the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

, thus essentially any geometry of the three pinholes can form the ridge
 triangle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Extraction of Ridge Lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to determine the ridge lines, rather than the straightforward way
 of observing individual interference fringes 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}(x,y)$
\end_inset

 by closing one of the holes, we extract all the ridge lines in a single
 shot from the combined interferogram 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x,y)$
\end_inset

.
 To start with, note that for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b},\,\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\mathbf{b}.\mathbf{\nabla}\left(\mathbf{k}.\mathbf{r}\right) & =b_{i}\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{i}}k_{j}r_{j}\\
 & =b_{i}k_{j}\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{i}}r_{j}\right)\\
 & =b_{i}k_{j}\delta_{ij}\\
 & =\mathbf{b}.\mathbf{k}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Now we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{b}_{i}\equiv\mathbf{e}_{z}\times(\mathbf{a}_{j}-\mathbf{a}_{k})=\frac{L}{k}\mathbf{e}_{z}\times\mathbf{k}_{jk}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j,k)=(1,2,3),(2,3,1),(3,1,2)$
\end_inset

 NB: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{i}\mathbf{k}_{jk}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Further note that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 is determined only by the geometry of the three pinholes.
 If we consider the directional derivative along 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{jk}$
\end_inset

 we can
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The derivation is given below.
 This is just to motivate the approach.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 now eliminate one of the interference fringes 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}(x,y)$
\end_inset

 from the total interferogram 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x,y)$
\end_inset

 while the other fringes remain sinusoidal functions.
 Another such directional derivative isolates the desired oscillation term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's explicitly derive this.
 Recall: 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}(x,y)\equiv2\left(1+\cos\left[(\mathbf{k}_{ij}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{ij}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{i}|\psi_{j}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{i}|\psi_{j}\right\rangle \right|\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let's start with performing the first directional derivative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\left(\mathbf{b}_{1}.\nabla\right)p(x,y) & =\left(\mathbf{b}_{1}.\mathbf{\nabla}\right)\frac{C^{2}}{L^{2}}\left\{ -3+\sum_{(i,j)\text{cycle}}P_{ij}(x,y)\right\} \\
 & \propto\sum_{(i,k)\text{cycle}}\left(\mathbf{b}_{1}.\mathbf{\nabla}\right)P_{ik}(x,y)\\
 & \propto\sin\left[(\mathbf{k}_{12}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{12}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right|\cancelto{\mathbf{b}_{1}.\mathbf{k}_{12}}{\left(\mathbf{b}_{1}.\mathbf{\nabla}\right)(\mathbf{k}_{12}.\mathbf{r})}\\
 & +\sin\left[(\mathbf{k}_{23}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{23}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{2}|\psi_{3}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{2}|\psi_{3}\right\rangle \right|\cancelto{0}{\mathbf{b}_{1}.\mathbf{k}_{23}}\\
 & +\sin\left[(\mathbf{k}_{31}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{31}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{3}|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{3}|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \right|\mathbf{b}_{1}.\mathbf{k}_{31}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Now when it is applied again along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\left(\mathbf{b}_{2}.\nabla\right)\left(\mathbf{b}_{1}.\nabla\right)p(x,y) & \propto-\cos\left[(\mathbf{k}_{12}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{12}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right|\mathbf{b}_{1}.\mathbf{k}_{12}\mathbf{b}_{2}.\mathbf{k}_{12}\\
 & -\cos\left[(\mathbf{k}_{31}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{31}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{3}|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{3}|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \right|\mathbf{b}_{1}.\mathbf{k}_{31}\cancelto{0}{\mathbf{b}_{2}.\mathbf{k}_{31}}\\
 & \propto\cos\left[(\mathbf{k}_{12}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{12}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \right|
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

which is precisely what we'd claimed to start with.
 NB: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{b}_{2}.\nabla\right)\left(\mathbf{b}_{1}.\nabla\right)p(x,y)=\left(\mathbf{b}_{1}.\nabla\right)\left(\mathbf{b}_{2}.\nabla\right)p(x,y)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So in general then, I can write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\mathbf{b}_{i}.\mathbf{\nabla}\right)\left(\mathbf{b}_{j}.\mathbf{\nabla}\right)p(x,y)\propto\cos\left[(\mathbf{k}_{ij}.\mathbf{r})-\phi_{ij}+\text{arg}\left\langle \psi_{i}|\psi_{j}\right\rangle \right]\left|\left\langle \psi_{i}|\psi_{j}\right\rangle \right|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interferograms for the three pinholes are shown in Figure 3(a) and the three
 sets of ridge lines thus extracted are shown in Figure 3(b).
 Thus it is easy to determine the pure geometric phase instantaneously as
 the square root of the area of the ridge triangle extracted directly from
 the three pinhole interferogram for three arbitrary states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experiment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the experiment (Figure 2), a 
\begin_inset Formula $532nm$
\end_inset

 green laser source was used for illuminating a thin copper foil that is
 perforated with three 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1mm$
\end_inset

 radius pinholes.
 These pinholes lie on an equilateral triangle of side 
\begin_inset Formula $1.5mm$
\end_inset

.
 The observation plane was placed at a distance of approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $2m$
\end_inset

 from the pinholes, where the interfering patterns were captured using a
 charged coupled device (CCD) camera.
 This camera had a resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $640\times480$
\end_inset

 pixels with each pixel being 
\begin_inset Formula $9\mu m\times8\mu m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polarization states from the left, right and upper pinholes are 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}=(\sqrt{3}\ket{H}+i\ket{V})/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}=(i\sqrt{3}\ket{H}+\ket{V})/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{3}}=\cos\ket{H}+\sin\ket{V}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{V}$
\end_inset

 are the horizontal and vertical polarization states respectively.
 On the Poincare sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 are both located at a latitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm60^{o}$
\end_inset

 on the prime meridian and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{3}}$
\end_inset

 is located on the equator at a longitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\theta$
\end_inset

 which is can be varied according to linear polarizer LP1.
 The geometric phase is proportional to the solid angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 of the spherical triangle formed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{3}}$
\end_inset

 on the Poincare sphere as 
\begin_inset Formula $\arg\Delta_{3}=-\Omega/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\arg\Delta_{3}(\psi_{1}\psi_{2}\psi_{3})=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\tan\theta\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

